WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.328 --> 00:00:02.995
(gentle music)

2
00:00:09.005 --> 00:00:12.324
<v Announcer>We're gonna turn our attention</v>

3
00:00:12.324 --> 00:00:16.710
back to care of children and adolescents.

4
00:00:16.710 --> 00:00:20.250
Always a pleasure to welcome a friend and colleague,

5
00:00:20.250 --> 00:00:22.380
Dr. Janalynn Beste.

6
00:00:22.380 --> 00:00:25.290
Dr. Beste serves many roles in life,

7
00:00:25.290 --> 00:00:27.450
but she's currently a professor of family medicine

8
00:00:27.450 --> 00:00:28.770
at the University of North Carolina

9
00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:31.710
and she's the Program Director and Chair at Novant Health

10
00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:33.780
in New Hanover Regional Medical Center

11
00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:37.020
Residency in Family Medicine in Wilmington.

12
00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:39.060
Jan, thanks for being here. It's a pleasure.

13
00:00:39.060 --> 00:00:40.595
Good afternoon.
<v ->Thank you.</v>

14
00:00:40.595 --> 00:00:42.930
So I'm gonna talk to you about some fun topics today.

15
00:00:42.930 --> 00:00:44.430
I'm gonna talk to you about kids.

16
00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:46.590
So my practice, I'm a residency director.

17
00:00:46.590 --> 00:00:48.660
Our residency practice has about,

18
00:00:48.660 --> 00:00:51.090
35% of our patients are under the age of 18.

19
00:00:51.090 --> 00:00:53.730
So we've gotten very good at taking care of kids,

20
00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:56.640
so I'll try to throw in some pearls as well as board stuff.

21
00:00:56.640 --> 00:00:58.200
I have nothing to disclose.

22
00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:01.050
These are our learning objectives. We're gonna get going.

23
00:01:01.050 --> 00:01:03.510
Let's talk a little bit about newborn screening tests.

24
00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:06.330
The USPSTF, unlike everything else you know about,

25
00:01:06.330 --> 00:01:09.517
has no say in screening tests with newborns

26
00:01:09.517 --> 00:01:11.370
for inherited diseases.

27
00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:12.203
That's something through

28
00:01:12.203 --> 00:01:13.620
the Department of Health and Human Services.

29
00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:14.970
They have an advisory committee

30
00:01:14.970 --> 00:01:19.290
and they have a long list of recommended screening tests.

31
00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:21.090
Most of you have seen some of these.

32
00:01:21.090 --> 00:01:22.830
There's the metabolic disorders,

33
00:01:22.830 --> 00:01:24.360
there's the hemoglobinopathies,

34
00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:25.740
there's the endocrine disorders,

35
00:01:25.740 --> 00:01:28.560
and then there's some other just multi-system disorders.

36
00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:30.000
Now, as you probably all know,

37
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.330
every state has a different panel that they require.

38
00:01:33.330 --> 00:01:34.800
These are the ones recommended by

39
00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:38.820
the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.

40
00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:41.285
Okay, so for those of you who maybe haven't practiced

41
00:01:41.285 --> 00:01:43.769
newborn care in a while, there may be some new tests

42
00:01:43.769 --> 00:01:45.060
out there that you're not aware of

43
00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:46.440
and this may be one of them.

44
00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.450
This is a recommended screening test

45
00:01:48.450 --> 00:01:50.550
for congenital heart defects,

46
00:01:50.550 --> 00:01:53.100
and so these are your heart defects that

47
00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:55.320
typically cause you to become hypoxemic.

48
00:01:55.320 --> 00:01:58.500
So you can see the the big targets for this:

49
00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:01.680
your hypoplastic left heart, your Tetrology of Fallot,

50
00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:03.889
your transposition of the great arteries.

51
00:02:03.889 --> 00:02:05.790
So how do you test for this?

52
00:02:05.790 --> 00:02:08.040
So basically, you take your baby

53
00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:10.500
and they have to be over 24 hours of age.

54
00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:13.080
Why do they have to be over 24 hours of age?

55
00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:14.640
Sorry, I felt like I was talking to my residents;

56
00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:16.230
I was waiting for somebody to raise their hand.

57
00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:19.151
So the reason is because the ductus arteriosus closes

58
00:02:19.151 --> 00:02:20.803
and they go from fetal circulation

59
00:02:20.803 --> 00:02:22.980
to extra uterine circulation.

60
00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:24.780
So you have to wait that 24 hours, and then you put

61
00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:27.960
a pulse ox on their right hand and on one of their feet

62
00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:30.000
and you measure their oxygen levels.

63
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:31.800
It should be above 95%

64
00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:33.540
in both the right hand and the right foot,

65
00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:35.432
and there should be less than a 3% difference

66
00:02:35.432 --> 00:02:37.500
between those two.

67
00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:39.457
If they don't pass that one, you say,

68
00:02:39.457 --> 00:02:40.844
"Okay, maybe this kid's a little slow;

69
00:02:40.844 --> 00:02:42.120
let's give them another hour."

70
00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:43.290
You check it again.

71
00:02:43.290 --> 00:02:45.600
They don't pass that one, you give 'em one more chance,

72
00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:47.190
and if they don't pass that,

73
00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:49.320
then they go for an echocardiogram.

74
00:02:49.320 --> 00:02:51.930
So two failed screens are,

75
00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:55.680
or if your oximetry is less than 90% at any time,

76
00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:57.960
just send them for an echocardiogram.

77
00:02:57.960 --> 00:02:59.700
Okay, the other screening test

78
00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:01.110
that's maybe new for some of you

79
00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.050
is universal screening for hearing loss in newborns,

80
00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:05.970
and that's because 50% of newborns

81
00:03:05.970 --> 00:03:07.590
have no identifiable risk factors;

82
00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:09.150
so they recommend screen all of them.

83
00:03:09.150 --> 00:03:12.030
And so as you know, the reason why we screen for things

84
00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:15.480
is because we have things that we can do about it.

85
00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:18.346
And so it's been shown that if you screen them

86
00:03:18.346 --> 00:03:22.710
and diagnose them early and refer them for treatment,

87
00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:23.899
they actually have better language skills

88
00:03:23.899 --> 00:03:25.290
by the time they hit school.

89
00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:27.144
So this is a screening test that actually has good outcomes

90
00:03:27.144 --> 00:03:28.770
if we do something about it.

91
00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:30.450
If you see a kid in your practice

92
00:03:30.450 --> 00:03:32.310
fail their newborn screen, you need to make sure

93
00:03:32.310 --> 00:03:34.980
they have followed up by three months.

94
00:03:34.980 --> 00:03:36.810
Developmental dysplasia of the hip.

95
00:03:36.810 --> 00:03:39.660
Somehow this shows up on boards randomly,

96
00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:41.790
so I thought I'd take a minute and go over it.

97
00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:43.890
So your risk factors in infants

98
00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:47.160
are not great predictive values, but if you have a child

99
00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:49.200
who was breached in the third trimester,

100
00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:50.820
even if they turned vertex at the end;

101
00:03:50.820 --> 00:03:52.830
so if they had a version and turned vertex,

102
00:03:52.830 --> 00:03:55.710
they're still counted as someone with a risk factor.

103
00:03:55.710 --> 00:03:57.420
Here's a trick or a tip.

104
00:03:57.420 --> 00:03:59.963
Anytime in pediatrics that there's a family history,

105
00:03:59.963 --> 00:04:01.834
the child is almost always at a higher risk,

106
00:04:01.834 --> 00:04:03.180
so just keep that in mind.

107
00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:04.080
If there's a family history

108
00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:05.730
of developmental dysplasia of the hip,

109
00:04:05.730 --> 00:04:07.140
child is at higher risk.

110
00:04:07.140 --> 00:04:09.750
Or if you have a history of improper swaddling,

111
00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:11.490
this always image to me is very funny

112
00:04:11.490 --> 00:04:13.920
because it's the hips extended and abducted,

113
00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:15.870
which basically means they're wrapping 'em like a mummy.

114
00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:17.790
I don't know anybody who wraps their babies like that,

115
00:04:17.790 --> 00:04:20.370
but if you do that, that's not good.

116
00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:21.390
So how do you test this?

117
00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:24.150
This is where you put your hands behind the hips

118
00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:27.150
and you try to posteriorly dislocate the femur,

119
00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:28.860
and you should feel a clunk.

120
00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:29.947
If you feel a click or you're like,

121
00:04:29.947 --> 00:04:31.440
"I'm not sure what that is," it's not it.

122
00:04:31.440 --> 00:04:33.480
It needs to be a clunk.

123
00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:35.820
The board question is often, "What do you do with that?"

124
00:04:35.820 --> 00:04:37.440
You refer them to orthopedics.

125
00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:39.120
You do not get an ultrasound. You don't get an X-ray.

126
00:04:39.120 --> 00:04:40.193
You just send them straight to orthopedics

127
00:04:40.193 --> 00:04:42.360
if you fail that on your exam.

128
00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:45.450
The ultrasound is not accurate until about 6 weeks of age.

129
00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:48.960
Once those little bony centers start ossifying,

130
00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:51.960
you start doing X-rays, which is about four to six months,

131
00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:53.489
and you should do this up until they're walking

132
00:04:53.489 --> 00:04:55.623
because this is developmental.

133
00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:00.478
Okay, there is one, a recommendation from the USPSTF,

134
00:05:00.478 --> 00:05:04.145
and that is to put ocular prophylaxis for gonorrhea

135
00:05:04.145 --> 00:05:05.640
in their eyes at birth.

136
00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:07.860
And erythromycin is the drug that we use.

137
00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:10.140
You'll see most of the nursing staff,

138
00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:12.240
or if you're doing this at home births,

139
00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.060
they'll do this within the first few hours of life.

140
00:05:15.060 --> 00:05:17.130
Okay, our first question.

141
00:05:17.130 --> 00:05:18.840
First question is about Vitamin D.

142
00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:20.919
How much Vitamin D supplementation do infants need

143
00:05:20.919 --> 00:05:24.210
during the first month of life?

144
00:05:24.210 --> 00:05:25.350
Breastfed infants should have

145
00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:28.290
400 international units of Vitamin D daily,

146
00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:31.050
Milk-based formula-fed infants do not need

147
00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:33.390
any Vitamin D supplementation,

148
00:05:33.390 --> 00:05:35.730
Infants fed combined breastmilk and milk-based formula

149
00:05:35.730 --> 00:05:38.490
should have 200 international units of Vitamin D,

150
00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:41.790
or No Vitamin D supplementation is needed

151
00:05:41.790 --> 00:05:44.343
during the first month of life.

152
00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:53.280
All right, excellent. About half of you got it right.

153
00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:55.650
So let's talk about Vitamin D.

154
00:05:55.650 --> 00:05:58.300
So breastmilk does not have a lot of Vitamin D in it,

155
00:05:59.190 --> 00:06:02.268
but all infants should have Vitamin D

156
00:06:02.268 --> 00:06:04.560
starting the first few days of life.

157
00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:07.500
So formula-fed infants finally get enough Vitamin D

158
00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.967
once they're taking about a liter or 32 ounces

159
00:06:09.967 --> 00:06:13.140
of Vitamin D-fortified formula.

160
00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:15.270
Somewhere around three to four months of age,

161
00:06:15.270 --> 00:06:17.445
unless some of my parents two weeks of age

162
00:06:17.445 --> 00:06:19.910
have already said, "I don't know why my baby's spitting up.

163
00:06:19.910 --> 00:06:22.167
Been feeding them 32 ounces of formula."

164
00:06:23.068 --> 00:06:25.315
Breastfed infants should continue on Vitamin D

165
00:06:25.315 --> 00:06:27.810
up until they're on Vitamin D-fortified milk,

166
00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:30.210
so typically around a year of age.

167
00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:32.383
Or, breastfeeding mothers can take

168
00:06:32.383 --> 00:06:35.406
6,400 international units of Vitamin D.

169
00:06:35.406 --> 00:06:36.780
That's the official number.

170
00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:39.450
Obviously, they can take 10,000 a day.

171
00:06:39.450 --> 00:06:40.710
So the other supplementation,

172
00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:42.690
so Vitamin D for all babies

173
00:06:42.690 --> 00:06:44.362
starting within a few days of birth,

174
00:06:44.362 --> 00:06:48.090
iron supplementation is for your breastfed infants

175
00:06:48.090 --> 00:06:50.220
starting one milligram per kilogram per day

176
00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:51.210
starting at four months.

177
00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:52.620
Babies are born with iron stores,

178
00:06:52.620 --> 00:06:54.948
but around four months of age they start to peter out,

179
00:06:54.948 --> 00:06:58.440
so this is where you start your breastfed infants on iron.

180
00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:00.515
Formula-fed infants, please make sure they're taking

181
00:07:00.515 --> 00:07:02.640
iron-fortified formula.

182
00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:05.250
Now, there's something different for premature infants,

183
00:07:05.250 --> 00:07:07.860
and premature is less than 37 weeks.

184
00:07:07.860 --> 00:07:10.488
All of those infants should be put on iron,

185
00:07:10.488 --> 00:07:12.300
whether they're breastfeeding or iron.

186
00:07:12.300 --> 00:07:14.190
You see there's two different doses for breastfeeding,

187
00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:15.023
it's a little bit higher,

188
00:07:15.023 --> 00:07:17.040
it's two milligrams per kilogram per day,

189
00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:18.060
whereas for formula feeding

190
00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:19.740
it's one milligram per kilogram per day.

191
00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:21.449
And that's for the whole first year of life

192
00:07:21.449 --> 00:07:22.740
for premature infants;

193
00:07:22.740 --> 00:07:24.730
so if you take care of preemies in your office,

194
00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:28.680
please be aware you have to think about Vitamin D and iron.

195
00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:29.730
So breastfeeding.

196
00:07:29.730 --> 00:07:32.700
Six months of exclusive breastfeeding is recommended

197
00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:35.190
by the American Academy of Pediatrics.

198
00:07:35.190 --> 00:07:37.049
They recommend then starting food at six months of age

199
00:07:37.049 --> 00:07:38.616
and then breastfeeding can continue

200
00:07:38.616 --> 00:07:41.100
as long as mom and baby desire.

201
00:07:41.100 --> 00:07:42.630
That can be up to two years of age

202
00:07:42.630 --> 00:07:44.850
or even longer in some places.

203
00:07:44.850 --> 00:07:46.080
Couple of things that have been shown

204
00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:47.340
to help with breastfeeding.

205
00:07:47.340 --> 00:07:49.950
Those of you who have either been in a delivery room,

206
00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:51.240
or heard about delivery rooms,

207
00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:52.500
or have families in delivery rooms,

208
00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:54.570
know that no longer do we take the baby

209
00:07:54.570 --> 00:07:56.730
and whisk them away over to the warmer.

210
00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:58.620
We actually hand the baby to the mom

211
00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:00.248
and they put the baby right on the mom's chest.

212
00:08:00.248 --> 00:08:02.160
That's called skin-to-skin.

213
00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.570
It does improve breastfeeding rates.

214
00:08:03.570 --> 00:08:05.880
It also helps with temperature regulation,

215
00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:08.460
breathing, heart rate, all the things that we want

216
00:08:08.460 --> 00:08:10.140
that are good for babies.

217
00:08:10.140 --> 00:08:12.129
Professional and layperson support

218
00:08:12.129 --> 00:08:15.378
also increases breastfeeding rates, so that's help.

219
00:08:15.378 --> 00:08:16.856
You can actually monitor

220
00:08:16.856 --> 00:08:19.440
their milk intake by weighing them.

221
00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:20.467
So if you have a mom who's like,

222
00:08:20.467 --> 00:08:21.750
"This baby's getting no milk,"

223
00:08:21.750 --> 00:08:24.270
you can actually weigh them before and after a feeding.

224
00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:25.833
And if they have tongue tie,

225
00:08:26.970 --> 00:08:28.440
fixing that tongue tie will often help

226
00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:29.520
with nipple-related pain,

227
00:08:29.520 --> 00:08:31.860
and if you can fix mom's nipple-related pain,

228
00:08:31.860 --> 00:08:33.900
she's more likely to breastfeed.

229
00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:37.230
Lots and lots of baby benefits for breastfeeding;

230
00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:39.570
so you can see the whole list here.

231
00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:41.467
The ones most of us know about is obesity

232
00:08:41.467 --> 00:08:43.920
and otitis and infections;

233
00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:46.110
you may not know diabetes, hypertension.

234
00:08:46.110 --> 00:08:48.910
Look at all these great things breastfeeding helps with.

235
00:08:49.746 --> 00:08:52.764
Maternal benefits may be a little less well-defined,

236
00:08:52.764 --> 00:08:55.590
but we do know there's a decreased risk of breast cancer,

237
00:08:55.590 --> 00:08:57.300
ovarian cancer, endometrial cancer;

238
00:08:57.300 --> 00:09:00.180
and also, look at that, diabetes and hypertension.

239
00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:02.880
There's not a lot of contraindications.

240
00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:04.140
I don't know about you, but I don't see

241
00:09:04.140 --> 00:09:07.353
a lot of Ebola or untreated brucellosis.

242
00:09:08.550 --> 00:09:09.750
The biggest ones that I see

243
00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:11.820
are maternal active, maternal substance use

244
00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:14.220
because, obviously, anything that's going into the mom

245
00:09:14.220 --> 00:09:15.240
will be going into the baby;

246
00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:17.126
so you need to have a pretty significant conversation

247
00:09:17.126 --> 00:09:18.750
with your mom about that.

248
00:09:18.750 --> 00:09:20.700
I find that mostly conversations with my moms

249
00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:22.434
who are recreational marijuana users

250
00:09:22.434 --> 00:09:24.408
in a state where it is not legal.

251
00:09:24.408 --> 00:09:26.104
And whether it's legal or not, it doesn't matter.

252
00:09:26.104 --> 00:09:28.320
There's some impact for the baby.

253
00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:29.670
Okay, some feeding pearls.

254
00:09:29.670 --> 00:09:31.424
If they are using formula, please make sure

255
00:09:31.424 --> 00:09:33.530
they're using iron formula.

256
00:09:33.530 --> 00:09:34.710
It should be at room temperature;

257
00:09:34.710 --> 00:09:36.690
don't heat it in the microwave.

258
00:09:36.690 --> 00:09:37.680
Make sure that you switch to

259
00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:40.500
Vitamin D-fortified cow's milk at one year.

260
00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:41.618
You can use soy formula

261
00:09:41.618 --> 00:09:43.264
for those who are vegetarian families

262
00:09:43.264 --> 00:09:45.990
or have some histories of allergies.

263
00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:48.810
Recommendation to start foods, not a lot of evidence-based.

264
00:09:48.810 --> 00:09:52.470
This is sort of the C recommendations.

265
00:09:52.470 --> 00:09:54.180
Start cereals about four to six months.

266
00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:55.560
Vegetables, fruits and table foods.

267
00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:57.210
Don't do honey in the first year.

268
00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.630
And, so this is something that does come up on the boards.

269
00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:02.310
If you're at a high risk for peanut allergy,

270
00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:04.290
so if there's a lot of peanut allergies in the family,

271
00:10:04.290 --> 00:10:05.790
you should introduce peanut containing foods

272
00:10:05.790 --> 00:10:07.201
in those first set of foods.

273
00:10:07.201 --> 00:10:10.380
So not peanuts, just to be clear;

274
00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:13.710
like peanut butter or something else that contains peanuts.

275
00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:14.543
Had somebody ask me that:

276
00:10:14.543 --> 00:10:16.020
"Oh, should I just give my kid peanuts?"

277
00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:18.180
No, don't give your kid peanuts.

278
00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:20.141
Here's your nutrition pearls.

279
00:10:20.141 --> 00:10:21.851
Babies should have a couple of stools a day,

280
00:10:21.851 --> 00:10:23.250
several wet diapers a day.

281
00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:24.480
They should regain their birth weight

282
00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:25.777
in the first two weeks.

283
00:10:25.777 --> 00:10:27.859
They can lose up to 10% of their body weight

284
00:10:27.859 --> 00:10:29.749
in that first two weeks and then regain it,

285
00:10:29.749 --> 00:10:31.380
and they should double their birth weight

286
00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:33.330
by four to six months, triple at a year.

287
00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:34.503
Okay, next question.

288
00:10:35.370 --> 00:10:37.410
Following a scheduled repeat C-section delivery,

289
00:10:37.410 --> 00:10:40.800
a term infant has a respiratory rate greater than 60.

290
00:10:40.800 --> 00:10:42.810
What is the treatment for the most common cause

291
00:10:42.810 --> 00:10:45.030
of this condition?

292
00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:47.670
So, do you do a septic workup and antibiotics,

293
00:10:47.670 --> 00:10:49.320
do you do a chest tube,

294
00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:52.260
do intubation and suction immediately after delivery,

295
00:10:52.260 --> 00:10:55.023
or do you supportive care with oxygen?

296
00:11:00.489 --> 00:11:01.322
Excellent.

297
00:11:01.322 --> 00:11:02.790
Most of you realize that you should be

298
00:11:02.790 --> 00:11:04.380
doing supportive care with oxygen

299
00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:06.990
because this is transient to get of the newborn.

300
00:11:06.990 --> 00:11:09.390
This is the most common cause of respiratory distress,

301
00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:12.480
unfortunately, in newborns, up to a half of them.

302
00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:13.830
It's a diagnosis of exclusion;

303
00:11:13.830 --> 00:11:15.210
you can't assume that's what it is

304
00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:16.860
until you've looked at everything else.

305
00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:19.261
If you did a chest X-ray, you'd see some diffuse,

306
00:11:19.261 --> 00:11:22.050
sort of patchy infiltrates.

307
00:11:22.050 --> 00:11:24.480
We used to call this retained fetal lung fluid,

308
00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:26.880
for those of you who may be a little bit older.

309
00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:28.343
Most of the time, it goes away quickly.

310
00:11:28.343 --> 00:11:30.030
It can last 72 hours.

311
00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:34.290
The longest I ever saw was five days, stumped all of us.

312
00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:35.610
And all you do is you put them on oxygen,

313
00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:38.250
give them some nasal CPAP, and wait for it to go away

314
00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:40.320
after you've made sure it's not one of these things.

315
00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:41.580
So if they are a premature infant,

316
00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:44.190
you need to think about respiratory distress syndrome.

317
00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:47.455
If they had meconium, think about meconium aspiration.

318
00:11:47.455 --> 00:11:51.062
Obviously, if there was a history of a maternal,

319
00:11:51.062 --> 00:11:53.270
like untreated GBS or something like that,

320
00:11:53.270 --> 00:11:55.110
you need to think about pneumonia.

321
00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:56.608
And, of course, if maybe they had to have

322
00:11:56.608 --> 00:11:58.590
some positive pressure ventilation, you might need

323
00:11:58.590 --> 00:12:00.750
to think about a pneumothorax.

324
00:12:00.750 --> 00:12:02.070
Heart murmurs.

325
00:12:02.070 --> 00:12:03.540
Again, if you don't see them in the hospital,

326
00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:04.580
you may see them in your office

327
00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:07.770
and the mom say, "Oh my gosh, my baby had a heart murmur."

328
00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:09.870
Most heart murmurs are transitional and benign.

329
00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:12.752
So the most common thing we see is right after delivery,

330
00:12:12.752 --> 00:12:15.070
you're hearing a murmur because you're starting

331
00:12:15.070 --> 00:12:17.880
to hear that ductus arteriosus as it's closing,

332
00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:20.190
and then 24 hours later it's gone.

333
00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:21.895
It's really fun to do with medical students.

334
00:12:21.895 --> 00:12:24.301
Pathologic murmurs are your loud murmurs,

335
00:12:24.301 --> 00:12:27.234
your harsh murmurs, continuous murmurs,

336
00:12:27.234 --> 00:12:29.640
and anytime the kid doesn't look good,

337
00:12:29.640 --> 00:12:32.640
the kid's turning blue while feeding or is lethargic.

338
00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:35.730
Don't blow off that murmur. None of you would anyway.

339
00:12:35.730 --> 00:12:36.993
Okay, next question.

340
00:12:37.890 --> 00:12:39.180
Let's talk about breastfeeding,

341
00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:40.680
another big one on the boards.

342
00:12:40.680 --> 00:12:44.160
Breastfeeding jaundice is characterized by:

343
00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:46.890
Onset after seven days of life,

344
00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:50.130
Persistence longer than one month of life,

345
00:12:50.130 --> 00:12:53.823
Insufficient feeds, or Frequent stools.

346
00:12:59.820 --> 00:13:01.265
All right, excellent, about half of you realize

347
00:13:01.265 --> 00:13:04.410
that this is insufficient feeding.

348
00:13:04.410 --> 00:13:06.161
So let's back up a little bit and talk a little bit

349
00:13:06.161 --> 00:13:08.250
about physiologic jaundice.

350
00:13:08.250 --> 00:13:10.980
So newborns conjugate bilirubin slower,

351
00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:12.937
they have more red blood cells being busted up

352
00:13:12.937 --> 00:13:16.200
after that delivery, and they have decreased excretion;

353
00:13:16.200 --> 00:13:18.474
and so physiologically they do have a rise.

354
00:13:18.474 --> 00:13:22.080
If you tested bilirubin on all babies, which we do,

355
00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:23.490
you will see usually a little bit

356
00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:26.220
of a rise in that bilirubin just normally.

357
00:13:26.220 --> 00:13:29.370
It peaks a couple of days, three to five days after birth,

358
00:13:29.370 --> 00:13:31.230
and usually by two weeks it's fine.

359
00:13:31.230 --> 00:13:33.780
In preterm infants, all of this is magnified.

360
00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:35.095
So they tend to go to higher levels,

361
00:13:35.095 --> 00:13:36.450
they tend to last longer

362
00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:39.063
because their livers are even less prepared to handle this

363
00:13:39.063 --> 00:13:41.400
than a term infant is.

364
00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:43.651
So neonatal hyper bilirubin is

365
00:13:43.651 --> 00:13:45.596
a total serum or plasma bilirubin

366
00:13:45.596 --> 00:13:47.340
greater than the 95th percentile

367
00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:50.070
on the hour-specific Bhutani nomogram,

368
00:13:50.070 --> 00:13:51.917
which is a nice little chart that tells you

369
00:13:51.917 --> 00:13:55.833
how high the bilirubin should be at each hour of life.

370
00:13:57.390 --> 00:13:58.590
And I'm gonna point out,

371
00:13:58.590 --> 00:14:01.080
for those of you who either were not aware

372
00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:04.890
or just want to do some fun extra reading,

373
00:14:04.890 --> 00:14:06.480
the American Academy of Pediatrics put out

374
00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:08.280
some new hyperbilirubinemia guidelines

375
00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:10.920
for the first time in quite some time in 2022;

376
00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:12.090
and so I'm gonna go through some of the changes

377
00:14:12.090 --> 00:14:13.590
that they said there.

378
00:14:13.590 --> 00:14:17.430
So they recommend that they do universal newborn screening.

379
00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:18.510
You can do targeted screening;

380
00:14:18.510 --> 00:14:20.880
I don't know anybody who does target screening.

381
00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:24.090
So what is severe hyperbilirubinemia?

382
00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:26.310
If you get a total bilirubin greater than 20,

383
00:14:26.310 --> 00:14:28.290
that's considered severe.

384
00:14:28.290 --> 00:14:29.940
And why do we worry about this?

385
00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:33.041
Well, bilirubin crosses the blood-brain barrier

386
00:14:33.041 --> 00:14:34.906
and can attach to the brain tissue

387
00:14:34.906 --> 00:14:37.590
and can cause neurologic dysfunction.

388
00:14:37.590 --> 00:14:41.297
So you can have the acute bilirubin encephalopathy,

389
00:14:41.297 --> 00:14:42.930
or if you leave it alone,

390
00:14:42.930 --> 00:14:44.299
it can actually turn into permanent brain damage,

391
00:14:44.299 --> 00:14:45.843
which is kernicterus.

392
00:14:46.732 --> 00:14:49.350
Okay, so you have babies who are at risk

393
00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:51.161
for developing hyperbilirubinemia,

394
00:14:51.161 --> 00:14:54.360
so the risk of getting that bilirubin above 20.

395
00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:55.376
And you'll see this nice long list;

396
00:14:55.376 --> 00:14:56.790
I'm gonna point out a few things.

397
00:14:56.790 --> 00:15:00.660
One is exclusive breastfeeding with suboptimal intake.

398
00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:02.790
That was our board question we talked about.

399
00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:05.670
Oh, look at this: parent or sibling received phototherapy.

400
00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:07.680
Remember what I said, if it's in the family,

401
00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:09.690
they're more likely to have it as well.

402
00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:11.010
Lower gestational age.

403
00:15:11.010 --> 00:15:13.110
The earlier the baby is, the more likely they are

404
00:15:13.110 --> 00:15:15.423
to develop severe hyperbilirubinemia.

405
00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:17.812
Hemolytic disease.

406
00:15:17.812 --> 00:15:19.920
And the one thing I wanna point out, so this is something

407
00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:22.380
that was new in the last set of guidelines.

408
00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:23.818
This family history of genetic ancestry

409
00:15:23.818 --> 00:15:26.137
suggestive of inherited RBC disorders

410
00:15:26.137 --> 00:15:30.510
including glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency.

411
00:15:30.510 --> 00:15:31.710
I remember learning about that

412
00:15:31.710 --> 00:15:33.270
and I never really thought about it,

413
00:15:33.270 --> 00:15:34.470
but I want you to look at those numbers:

414
00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.060
13% of African American males

415
00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:39.226
and 4% of African American females have G6PD deficiency.

416
00:15:39.226 --> 00:15:41.130
Over the past few years,

417
00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:43.498
almost all of our people who unexpectedly,

418
00:15:43.498 --> 00:15:47.310
you know, bottle feeding moms, the bilirubin went to 20,

419
00:15:47.310 --> 00:15:49.953
had G6PD deficiency, so think about that.

420
00:15:50.933 --> 00:15:55.200
So of the kids who get that really high bilirubin level,

421
00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:59.310
these are the kids at risk for having neurotoxicity.

422
00:15:59.310 --> 00:16:01.020
So if they have a low albumin,

423
00:16:01.020 --> 00:16:05.083
if they have G6PD deficiency, if they are premature

424
00:16:05.083 --> 00:16:07.653
and if they're septic or have clinical instability.

425
00:16:08.700 --> 00:16:10.084
Okay, one of the nice things is

426
00:16:10.084 --> 00:16:13.080
that breastfeeding jaundice, they switched the name.

427
00:16:13.080 --> 00:16:15.306
It's now suboptimal intake hyperbilirubinemia,

428
00:16:15.306 --> 00:16:16.988
which I think makes it a little more obvious

429
00:16:16.988 --> 00:16:18.523
as to what it is.

430
00:16:18.523 --> 00:16:21.930
People used to confuse it with breastmilk jaundice.

431
00:16:21.930 --> 00:16:23.760
So breastfeeding jaundice is essentially

432
00:16:23.760 --> 00:16:27.000
an exaggeration of the normal physiologic jaundice.

433
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.130
It's the baby's not taking in enough,

434
00:16:29.130 --> 00:16:32.910
and usually they're feeding less than eight times a day,

435
00:16:32.910 --> 00:16:35.160
and so they aren't pooping out enough

436
00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:37.710
and the bilirubin just raises up.

437
00:16:37.710 --> 00:16:41.310
So what do you do? Tell mom to feed the baby more.

438
00:16:41.310 --> 00:16:42.570
You don't stop breastfeeding.

439
00:16:42.570 --> 00:16:43.920
You see that interrupting breastfeeding

440
00:16:43.920 --> 00:16:45.990
decreases your chances of success,

441
00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:47.760
and you can have them continue to breastfeed

442
00:16:47.760 --> 00:16:50.010
and usually tell them more frequently.

443
00:16:50.010 --> 00:16:51.830
I find this most often when they've been told

444
00:16:51.830 --> 00:16:54.513
you have to feed the baby every three hours.

445
00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:57.030
And anybody who's had a newborn knows

446
00:16:57.030 --> 00:16:58.620
babies don't feed on anybody's schedule;

447
00:16:58.620 --> 00:16:59.880
they feed when they're hungry,

448
00:16:59.880 --> 00:17:01.860
and that could be every 30 minutes.

449
00:17:01.860 --> 00:17:05.400
Breastmilk jaundice is a factor in breastmilk

450
00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:07.102
and it's usually not quite so high a level

451
00:17:07.102 --> 00:17:08.850
and it lasts a long time;

452
00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:10.039
so it sort of rises slowly

453
00:17:10.039 --> 00:17:13.473
and it can last up to a couple of months.

454
00:17:14.873 --> 00:17:17.700
So how do you treat it? You treat the underlying cause.

455
00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:19.784
If it's insufficient breastfeeding,

456
00:17:19.784 --> 00:17:22.350
they need to feed more frequently,

457
00:17:22.350 --> 00:17:24.060
so 8 plus times, I tell moms,

458
00:17:24.060 --> 00:17:26.839
10 to 12 times in 24 hours, give or take.

459
00:17:26.839 --> 00:17:28.505
There's nice tools out there.

460
00:17:28.505 --> 00:17:30.796
You can use online tools, or an app;

461
00:17:30.796 --> 00:17:32.670
BiliTool is one that we use.

462
00:17:32.670 --> 00:17:34.966
You can risk stratified and put in the bilirubin level

463
00:17:34.966 --> 00:17:36.660
and say, "Are we at a level where we need

464
00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:37.950
to think about treatment?"

465
00:17:37.950 --> 00:17:40.770
If you're going to treat, you treat with phototherapy.

466
00:17:40.770 --> 00:17:43.366
If you are high enough, you need to talk to your friends

467
00:17:43.366 --> 00:17:47.130
in neonatology world about an exchange transfusion.

468
00:17:47.130 --> 00:17:48.463
And again, if that jaundice persists,

469
00:17:48.463 --> 00:17:50.130
you need to think about something else;

470
00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:52.380
is there some other disease process going on?

471
00:17:53.415 --> 00:17:54.510
Failure to stool.

472
00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:56.327
Most of your babies will poop that thick black meconium

473
00:17:56.327 --> 00:17:58.260
in the first 12 hours of life.

474
00:17:58.260 --> 00:18:02.070
After 24 hours, please go and examine the baby.

475
00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:04.080
I always remember when I was a resident,

476
00:18:04.080 --> 00:18:05.639
one of my classmates missed the fact

477
00:18:05.639 --> 00:18:08.253
that the baby had an imperfect anus.

478
00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:10.710
He never lived that down;

479
00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:12.960
that went all throughout his career with him.

480
00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:14.378
And other things like cystic fibrosis,

481
00:18:14.378 --> 00:18:17.026
Hirschsprung's, et cetera.

482
00:18:17.026 --> 00:18:19.576
Okay, constipation: the bane of all of our existence.

483
00:18:19.576 --> 00:18:21.465
Moms come in, "Oh my gosh, my baby's constipated."

484
00:18:21.465 --> 00:18:22.830
You put in the thermometer and,

485
00:18:22.830 --> 00:18:24.990
boom, they poop and you fix them.

486
00:18:24.990 --> 00:18:26.940
So if that doesn't work, there's other things you can do.

487
00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:29.370
One is glycerin suppositories when they get old enough.

488
00:18:29.370 --> 00:18:33.480
You can do some of the high-fiber fruit juices.

489
00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:35.430
Miralax over the age of six months,

490
00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:38.880
you're gonna hear Miralax a lot, polyethylene glycol.

491
00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:40.920
High-fiber foods once they get older:

492
00:18:40.920 --> 00:18:42.544
that helps prevent constipation,

493
00:18:42.544 --> 00:18:44.880
it doesn't treat constipation.

494
00:18:44.880 --> 00:18:46.343
So think about if they come into you

495
00:18:46.343 --> 00:18:48.510
and they truly are constipated, you have to treat first

496
00:18:48.510 --> 00:18:51.360
before you start talking about putting 'em on prevention.

497
00:18:51.360 --> 00:18:52.440
Reflux.

498
00:18:52.440 --> 00:18:54.096
So there are two different things

499
00:18:54.096 --> 00:18:55.710
when you want to think about reflux.

500
00:18:55.710 --> 00:18:57.206
There is gastroesophageal reflux

501
00:18:57.206 --> 00:18:59.640
and gastroesophageal reflux disease.

502
00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:00.780
What's the difference?

503
00:19:00.780 --> 00:19:02.678
Reflux, pretty common and pretty normal;

504
00:19:02.678 --> 00:19:03.870
it's your happy spitters.

505
00:19:03.870 --> 00:19:06.205
You have a normal exam, weight gain,

506
00:19:06.205 --> 00:19:08.130
they're happy, they spit up,

507
00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:09.157
and basically you tell the mom,

508
00:19:09.157 --> 00:19:11.077
"They're growing good. Everything's fine.

509
00:19:11.077 --> 00:19:12.150
"Just make sure to always carry

510
00:19:12.150 --> 00:19:14.190
a couple changes of clothing with you."

511
00:19:14.190 --> 00:19:17.220
With the disease, then you have poor weight gain.

512
00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:19.830
They may be coughing, wheezing, seeming uncomfortable,

513
00:19:19.830 --> 00:19:23.239
and that's the group that you think about treating.

514
00:19:23.239 --> 00:19:25.348
So you can talk about thickened feedings

515
00:19:25.348 --> 00:19:27.690
to try to minimize regurgitation.

516
00:19:27.690 --> 00:19:29.310
You can use H2 blockers.

517
00:19:29.310 --> 00:19:32.490
We don't have a lot of great evidence for PPIs in infants.

518
00:19:32.490 --> 00:19:35.064
Sometimes when I send them to to PEDS GI,

519
00:19:35.064 --> 00:19:36.990
they will come back on that, but that's usually after

520
00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.430
we've tried everything else.

521
00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:40.797
You can try soy or hydrolyzed formulas

522
00:19:40.797 --> 00:19:42.240
and see if that makes a difference.

523
00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:43.680
You can try changing maternal diet

524
00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:45.380
to see if that makes a difference.

525
00:19:46.290 --> 00:19:48.330
Pyloric stenosis, this is a fun board question.

526
00:19:48.330 --> 00:19:49.950
And they'll always give you the classic case,

527
00:19:49.950 --> 00:19:52.078
which is a four-week-old white boy

528
00:19:52.078 --> 00:19:53.810
with nonbilious and projectile vomiting

529
00:19:53.810 --> 00:19:55.770
who throws up, seems hungry,

530
00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:57.901
eats, throws up, seems hungry.

531
00:19:57.901 --> 00:20:00.990
So that's sort of a classic board question.

532
00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:02.760
But other causes of vomiting...

533
00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:05.622
In my personal practice, the most common cause of vomiting

534
00:20:05.622 --> 00:20:09.210
is overfeeding those 32 ounces per day

535
00:20:09.210 --> 00:20:10.966
in the first two weeks of life.

536
00:20:10.966 --> 00:20:12.750
We already talked about reflux.

537
00:20:12.750 --> 00:20:14.417
And if the child looks ill, you need to think about

538
00:20:14.417 --> 00:20:17.880
more serious conditions like gastroenteritis, volvulus.

539
00:20:17.880 --> 00:20:20.676
And don't forget that shaken baby syndrome often presents

540
00:20:20.676 --> 00:20:24.450
with a child who's vomiting, so keep that in mind.

541
00:20:24.450 --> 00:20:26.582
Colic, known as the 10th circle of hell

542
00:20:26.582 --> 00:20:28.702
for parents who've experienced it,

543
00:20:28.702 --> 00:20:32.100
is uncontrollable crying for three hours per day,

544
00:20:32.100 --> 00:20:34.350
more than three days per week for longer than three weeks.

545
00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:36.821
The baby looks great in terms of weight gain,

546
00:20:36.821 --> 00:20:38.259
everything else is fine.

547
00:20:38.259 --> 00:20:41.040
Oh my gosh, it's the parents, though, who look terrible.

548
00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:44.052
The parents are haggard and thinking, "I'm a terrible mom.

549
00:20:44.052 --> 00:20:46.560
Somebody's gonna take this child away from me."

550
00:20:46.560 --> 00:20:48.750
There are some evidence-based things you can actually do.

551
00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:50.370
So if mom is breastfeeding,

552
00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:52.671
you can eliminate some allergens.

553
00:20:52.671 --> 00:20:57.463
You can actually give the baby the probiotic Lactobacillus

554
00:20:57.463 --> 00:21:00.165
in breastfeeding, but not formula-fed infants.

555
00:21:00.165 --> 00:21:01.962
With formula-fed infants, you can try switching

556
00:21:01.962 --> 00:21:04.041
to a hydrolyzed formula for a period of time

557
00:21:04.041 --> 00:21:05.550
and see if that helps.

558
00:21:05.550 --> 00:21:06.690
And most of them,

559
00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:08.580
thank god for the future of the human race,

560
00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:11.760
outgrow this by six months of age.

561
00:21:11.760 --> 00:21:15.582
I almost returned my son to sender when he had colic,

562
00:21:15.582 --> 00:21:17.673
and I'd gone back to working full time.

563
00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:22.046
Okay, undescended testicles

564
00:21:22.046 --> 00:21:24.270
are more common in premature boys.

565
00:21:24.270 --> 00:21:26.790
Most of the time, they descend by six months of age.

566
00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:28.620
So if you have a six-month-old child check,

567
00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:31.470
if you still can't feel those testicles,

568
00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:33.810
you need to refer them over to urology.

569
00:21:33.810 --> 00:21:34.989
And they will usually talk about surgery

570
00:21:34.989 --> 00:21:36.697
somewhere around 9 months of age,

571
00:21:36.697 --> 00:21:38.730
9 months to 12 months of age.

572
00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:41.682
So surgery will help preserve fertility.

573
00:21:41.682 --> 00:21:43.170
However, they still have

574
00:21:43.170 --> 00:21:45.330
a higher risk of testicular cancer.

575
00:21:45.330 --> 00:21:46.423
And that's something you need to tell the parents

576
00:21:46.423 --> 00:21:48.438
to make sure that they've told the child

577
00:21:48.438 --> 00:21:50.051
when he gets of an age to be

578
00:21:50.051 --> 00:21:51.750
paying attention to such things.

579
00:21:51.750 --> 00:21:53.308
And they can have testicular atrophy

580
00:21:53.308 --> 00:21:54.960
as a complication of surgery.

581
00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:57.290
I find that a lot of our surgeons don't discuss that.

582
00:21:57.290 --> 00:21:58.632
I've actually had one of my patients

583
00:21:58.632 --> 00:22:00.570
who had that complication from surgery

584
00:22:00.570 --> 00:22:02.730
and they were unaware.

585
00:22:02.730 --> 00:22:04.449
Okay, this is one of the scariest things

586
00:22:04.449 --> 00:22:05.930
I've ever seen in my career,

587
00:22:05.930 --> 00:22:08.610
and that is neonatal herpes simplex.

588
00:22:08.610 --> 00:22:10.620
It can present one of three ways.

589
00:22:10.620 --> 00:22:12.832
So it can present as just a localized skin infection,

590
00:22:12.832 --> 00:22:15.240
you know, like your herpetic whitlow kind of a thing.

591
00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:20.050
It can be in the central nervous system, so meningitis.

592
00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:23.340
Or, it can become disseminated disease,

593
00:22:23.340 --> 00:22:25.500
which was the case that I saw;

594
00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:27.363
and it has a 60% mortality rate

595
00:22:27.363 --> 00:22:29.100
even with appropriate treatment.

596
00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:30.157
Now, those of you who are like,

597
00:22:30.157 --> 00:22:31.311
"Well, I practice outpatient medicine,

598
00:22:31.311 --> 00:22:32.970
why do I need to worry about that?"

599
00:22:32.970 --> 00:22:35.031
Even if they have just the localized skin infection,

600
00:22:35.031 --> 00:22:36.599
so if you see a baby with a cold sore

601
00:22:36.599 --> 00:22:38.550
or with a little skin infection,

602
00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:40.283
you need to treat them with IV acyclovir

603
00:22:40.283 --> 00:22:44.310
because it can turn into disseminated disease

604
00:22:44.310 --> 00:22:45.783
with 60% mortality.

605
00:22:47.054 --> 00:22:48.960
Okay, hepatitis B.

606
00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:52.903
If you have a mom who is hepatitis B antigen positive,

607
00:22:52.903 --> 00:22:56.190
you'll give them both the vaccine and the immunoglobulin

608
00:22:56.190 --> 00:22:58.530
within the first 12 hours of birth.

609
00:22:58.530 --> 00:23:00.720
Now, let's say, mom, you don't know.

610
00:23:00.720 --> 00:23:03.420
You can give the hepatitis B vaccine as you normally would

611
00:23:03.420 --> 00:23:06.515
and then you can test the mom, and you have up until a week

612
00:23:06.515 --> 00:23:07.890
to give the immunoglobulins.

613
00:23:07.890 --> 00:23:09.589
So if you're following up a baby from the hospital,

614
00:23:09.589 --> 00:23:11.700
if you don't take care of them in the hospital,

615
00:23:11.700 --> 00:23:12.690
that's something you'd want to know

616
00:23:12.690 --> 00:23:14.173
is I need to follow those results and see about

617
00:23:14.173 --> 00:23:18.513
getting that given to the baby in that first week of life.

618
00:23:19.977 --> 00:23:21.776
What advice would you give parents to reduce

619
00:23:21.776 --> 00:23:24.690
the risk of death from sudden infant death syndrome,

620
00:23:24.690 --> 00:23:26.430
SIDS, in their infant?

621
00:23:26.430 --> 00:23:28.410
Would you tell them to stop breastfeeding,

622
00:23:28.410 --> 00:23:29.699
would you tell them that you should

623
00:23:29.699 --> 00:23:32.760
avoid exposure of the infant to second-hand smoke,

624
00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:36.180
you should place the baby in the prone position for sleep,

625
00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:38.763
or you should discourage the use of a pacifier?

626
00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:45.786
Okay. Oh, excellent.

627
00:23:45.786 --> 00:23:49.025
Most of you knew you should avoid exposure of the infant

628
00:23:49.025 --> 00:23:50.790
to secondhand smoke.

629
00:23:50.790 --> 00:23:53.156
So sudden infant death syndrome,

630
00:23:53.156 --> 00:23:56.190
peak incidence is at two to three months of age.

631
00:23:56.190 --> 00:23:59.610
And the things that you have to worry, those risk factors,

632
00:23:59.610 --> 00:24:00.958
are prone position...

633
00:24:00.958 --> 00:24:03.650
After Covid, if y'all don't know what proning is...

634
00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:06.960
We all have that burned into our minds right now.

635
00:24:06.960 --> 00:24:09.000
Proning is that face down position.

636
00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:10.852
Bed sharing, especially if mom or dad,

637
00:24:10.852 --> 00:24:13.410
or whoever's sharing the bed with them is impaired.

638
00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:16.680
Cigarette smoke exposure. All those things are bad.

639
00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:19.877
Protective: pacifiers, fans, and breastfeeding;

640
00:24:19.877 --> 00:24:21.300
all of those are good.

641
00:24:21.300 --> 00:24:22.980
And like with all of healthcare,

642
00:24:22.980 --> 00:24:25.530
there are some significant racial disparities.

643
00:24:25.530 --> 00:24:26.363
Sleep.

644
00:24:26.363 --> 00:24:27.660
So the American Academy of Pediatrics

645
00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:29.810
has a bunch of recommendations about sleep.

646
00:24:30.720 --> 00:24:31.920
Put the baby on their back

647
00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:34.080
every single time for every single sleep.

648
00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:35.853
Skin-to-skin, we talked about that.

649
00:24:36.844 --> 00:24:41.130
Firm, safe, flat sleep surface. Breastfeeding recommended.

650
00:24:41.130 --> 00:24:42.750
The baby should have their own little bed

651
00:24:42.750 --> 00:24:45.180
in close proximity to the mom for breastfeeding.

652
00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:46.722
Don't overheat them.

653
00:24:46.722 --> 00:24:49.290
Recommended that infants sleep in the parent's room,

654
00:24:49.290 --> 00:24:50.881
close to the parent's bed on a separate surface

655
00:24:50.881 --> 00:24:52.721
designed for infants, ideally for at least

656
00:24:52.721 --> 00:24:54.570
the first six months.

657
00:24:54.570 --> 00:24:56.204
And no naps in cars or strollers,

658
00:24:56.204 --> 00:24:59.010
(chuckles) written by somebody who's never had children.

659
00:24:59.010 --> 00:25:00.210
Okay, last question.

660
00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:01.675
The majority of failure to thrive cases

661
00:25:01.675 --> 00:25:03.390
in infants is due to:

662
00:25:03.390 --> 00:25:05.700
celiac disease, malabsorption syndrome,

663
00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:09.213
hyperthyroidism, or inadequate caloric intake.

664
00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:16.380
Excellent, inadequate caloric intake,

665
00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:18.201
so it's now growth faltering.

666
00:25:18.201 --> 00:25:21.060
It's basically inadequate growth, physical growth.

667
00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:22.495
You can't take just one point

668
00:25:22.495 --> 00:25:25.110
and say they have failure to thrive or growth faltering.

669
00:25:25.110 --> 00:25:27.840
You have to look at it over a couple of points.

670
00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:29.010
It occurs pretty frequently.

671
00:25:29.010 --> 00:25:30.170
You will see this if you take care of children

672
00:25:30.170 --> 00:25:31.680
in your practice.

673
00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:33.190
And the most common cause, by far,

674
00:25:33.190 --> 00:25:34.770
is just not enough calories.

675
00:25:34.770 --> 00:25:36.644
So why are they not getting enough calories?

676
00:25:36.644 --> 00:25:40.279
Maybe mom or dad is not preparing the formula correctly.

677
00:25:40.279 --> 00:25:43.230
Maybe they're having bad reflux and disease.

678
00:25:43.230 --> 00:25:44.728
Maybe there's just neglect and nobody's remembering

679
00:25:44.728 --> 00:25:46.927
to feed the baby, had a couple of those.

680
00:25:46.927 --> 00:25:49.152
"I thought you fed the baby." "I thought you fed the baby."

681
00:25:49.152 --> 00:25:51.060
Mechanical feeding problems.

682
00:25:51.060 --> 00:25:53.220
There are some times where they have inadequate absorption,

683
00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:55.470
like milk allergies or deficiencies.

684
00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:56.679
And, of course, increased metabolism;

685
00:25:56.679 --> 00:25:59.113
so if they have hyperthyroidism.

686
00:25:59.113 --> 00:26:00.527
Down syndrome is another one

687
00:26:00.527 --> 00:26:03.300
that can cause increased metabolism.

688
00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.449
All of those can cause the baby to be burning more calories

689
00:26:05.449 --> 00:26:07.380
than they're taking in.

690
00:26:07.380 --> 00:26:08.460
So how do you treat it?

691
00:26:08.460 --> 00:26:11.310
Well, like everything else, what's the underlying cause?

692
00:26:11.310 --> 00:26:14.760
If it's a inadequate calorie intake,

693
00:26:14.760 --> 00:26:16.623
you're going to think about a high calorie diet

694
00:26:16.623 --> 00:26:18.387
and you're going to make sure the parents

695
00:26:18.387 --> 00:26:20.040
are mixing formulas correctly,

696
00:26:20.040 --> 00:26:21.379
mom is feeding the baby frequently enough

697
00:26:21.379 --> 00:26:23.130
if she's breastfeeding.

698
00:26:23.130 --> 00:26:25.503
And if that doesn't seem to work,

699
00:26:25.503 --> 00:26:29.521
you may need to look at some other potential causes,

700
00:26:29.521 --> 00:26:31.770
so here's some of the tests you would order.

701
00:26:31.770 --> 00:26:33.463
You really should try not to hospitalize

702
00:26:33.463 --> 00:26:34.923
if at all possible.

703
00:26:37.260 --> 00:26:40.860
We sometimes do because we have a population

704
00:26:40.860 --> 00:26:42.011
with a lot of social risk factors

705
00:26:42.011 --> 00:26:44.280
and sometimes by hospitalizing it's the only way

706
00:26:44.280 --> 00:26:46.440
we can actually observe what's going on with the family.

707
00:26:46.440 --> 00:26:49.170
Most of the time, you do not need to hospitalize them.

708
00:26:49.170 --> 00:26:52.146
Okay, a couple last little bits and pieces.

709
00:26:52.146 --> 00:26:54.570
Lacrimal duct obstruction.

710
00:26:54.570 --> 00:26:56.382
Persistent tearing usually on one side.

711
00:26:56.382 --> 00:26:59.931
So mom will come and say, "This eye is always crusting.

712
00:26:59.931 --> 00:27:02.563
"Every time I wake up, I have to wipe it out

713
00:27:02.563 --> 00:27:04.290
every time the baby wakes up."

714
00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:06.288
So you can try putting some warm compresses on it,

715
00:27:06.288 --> 00:27:07.500
milking the duct;

716
00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:09.060
you don't need to do anything else.

717
00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:10.290
Keep an eye on it.

718
00:27:10.290 --> 00:27:12.120
Usually, if by a year it's still there,

719
00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:13.860
then you need to send them to an ophthalmologist

720
00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:15.560
to have them probe open that duct.

721
00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:18.529
So most of the parents have gotten that message

722
00:27:18.529 --> 00:27:20.386
about putting the baby on their back to sleep,

723
00:27:20.386 --> 00:27:22.192
and so they put them on their back in the car seat

724
00:27:22.192 --> 00:27:23.790
and put them on their back in the swing

725
00:27:23.790 --> 00:27:25.050
and they put them on their back in the bed;

726
00:27:25.050 --> 00:27:26.946
and they end up with positional plagiocephaly,

727
00:27:26.946 --> 00:27:29.610
which is some flattening in the back of the head.

728
00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:32.160
I think you've probably all seen these.

729
00:27:32.160 --> 00:27:35.068
Oftentimes, it'll be on one side

730
00:27:35.068 --> 00:27:36.570
because the baby usually will have

731
00:27:36.570 --> 00:27:38.640
a preferred side that they like to sleep on.

732
00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:40.285
So make sure that you're switching the head position

733
00:27:40.285 --> 00:27:41.813
and make sure they're doing tummy time.

734
00:27:41.813 --> 00:27:43.174
So tell the parents they only have to be

735
00:27:43.174 --> 00:27:45.240
on their back while they're sleeping.

736
00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:46.680
If you're in there with them or they're awake,

737
00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:48.005
put them on their tummy so they can practice,

738
00:27:48.005 --> 00:27:49.500
you know, putting their head up

739
00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:51.270
and also take the pressure off the back of the head.

740
00:27:51.270 --> 00:27:53.490
And if you have a kid who has that

741
00:27:53.490 --> 00:27:55.650
positional plagiocephaly on one side,

742
00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:57.600
make sure they don't have torticollis.

743
00:27:57.600 --> 00:27:59.790
Had a resident one time whose baby had that

744
00:27:59.790 --> 00:28:01.560
and she felt terrible that she had missed that,

745
00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:03.420
and I said, "Well, who would've thought?"

746
00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:05.370
Okay, frequent flyers. We talked about this.

747
00:28:05.370 --> 00:28:06.960
Hip dysplasia screening, breastfeeding,

748
00:28:06.960 --> 00:28:10.422
hyperbilirubinemia, Vitamin D, SIDS prevention.

749
00:28:10.422 --> 00:28:12.780
And here are your answers, in case y'all missed it.

750
00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:14.133
So thank you very much.

751
00:28:15.217 --> 00:28:17.884
(gentle music)

